sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1680025
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part encodes a reporter cassette for the Cre Recombinase (e.g parts XYZ) in Yeast. An active Cre protein will switch expression from RFP to NanoLuc luciferase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Nicolai von Kuegelgen

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: P0310
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Caroline Ajo-Franklin
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: genomic DNA of ADH1 from S. cerevisiae

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1680005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part contains the WT loxP site, which is recognised by Cre recombinase (Part BBa_K1680007), in forward orientation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Katharina Sporbeck

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: mRFP1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: **highly** engineered mutant of red fluorescent protein from Discosoma striata (coral)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: monomeric RFP: Red Fluorescent Protein. Excitation peak: 584 nm Emission peak: 607 nm
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Drew Endy
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Campbell et al., PNAS v99 p7877 URL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
TAATAA double stop codon added (DE).
Four silent mutations made to remove three EcoRI sites and one PstI site: A28G, A76G, A349G, G337A.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1680009
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Protein coding region for the NanoLuc(tm) Luziferase (designed by the Promega Corporation, free for research use), Codon optimized for yeast. The Nanoluc is smaller than other luziferase proteins and yields equal or stronger luminescence readings.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Katharina Sporbeck
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: gBlock designed by Team Tuebingen, sequence by Promega
